definition.value: A 2-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the phosphatidyl acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
A menaquinone whose side-chain contains 4 isoprene units in an all-trans-configuration.
Any substance that is distributed in foodstuffs. It includes materials derived from plants or animals, such as vitamins or minerals, as well as environmental contaminants.
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is propanoic acid in which one of the alpha-hydrogens is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A member of the class of benzaldehydes that is  salicylaldehyde substituted by a methoxy group at position 3.
A ketoheptose with a mannose configuration.
The open chain form of D-manno-heptulose.
A manno-heptulose with a D-configuration. It has been found in avocados.
A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl and the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are hexadecyl and propionyl respectively.
A 2-acyl-1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the alkyl and the acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are hexadecyl and butanoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 1-acyl group is specified as oleoyl.
An 11-hydroxylaurate obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of (11R)-hydroxylauric acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An anionic ganglioside obtained by deprotonation of the neuraminosyl carboxy group of ganglioside GM2; major species at pH 7.3.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate in which the 1-acyl substituent is specified as decanoyl.
A 1-(1Z)-alkenyl-2-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine in which the 2-acyl group is specified as acetyl.
Any pyrimidine that bears one or more carboxylic acid substituents.

Any organooxygen compound that is a polyhydroxy-aldehyde or -ketone, or a compound derived from one. Carbohydrates contain only carbon, hydrogen and oxygen and usually have an empirical formula Cm(H2O)n; carbohydrate derivatives may contain other elements by substitution or condensation.
A sphingomyelin 34:1 in which the N-acyl group and sphingoid base are specified as hexadecanoyl and sphingosine respectively.
A sphingomyelin 34:0 in which the N-acyl group and sphingoid base are specified as hexadecanoyl and sphinganine respectively.
A sphingomyelin 34:0 in which the N-acyl group and sphingoid base are specified as hexadecanoyl and phytosphingosine respectively.
A sphingomyelin that is phytosphingosine-1-phosphocholine having an unspecified fatty acyl group attached to the nitrogen.
A glycerophosphocholine that is glycero-3-phosphocholine substituted at positions 1 and 2 by octadecyl and methyl groups respectively.
A 1-octadecyl-2-methylglycero-3-phosphocholine that is the (R)-enantiomer of edelfosine.
A 1-octadecyl-2-methylglycero-3-phosphocholine that is the (S)-enantiomer of edelfosine.
An inorganic sodium salt in which chlorite is the counterion.
An aldehyde that is the acyclic form of ascarylose.
An inorganic sodium salt consisting of sodium and chromate ions in a 2:1 ratio.
An inorganic chloride composed of rubidium and chloride ions in a 1:1 ratio.
A ketohexose monophosphate that is D-fructose having a phospahte substituent at position 6. It is an important intermediate in the carbohydrate metabolism.

A poly(ether) macromolecule that is polyethylene glycol in which one of the terminal hydroxy groups has been converted to the corresponding p-octylphenyl ether. A nonionic, non-denaturing detergent, it is used for solubilising membrane proteins during isolation of membrane-protein complexes. n ~ 8.
A C27, very long straight-chain, saturated fatty acid.
A hydroxyether that is ethylene glycol substituted on one of the oxygens by a dodecyl group.
A lactol that is the pyranose form of ascarylose.
An ascarylopyranose that has alpha configuration at the anomeric centre.
An ascarylopyranose that has beta configuration at the anomeric centre.
A straight-chain, saturated fatty acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of pentadecanoic acid. It is the major species at pH 7.3.
A nineteen carbon straight-chain fatty acid anion. Major species at pH 7.3.
A long-chain fatty acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of henicosanoic acid. Major species at pH 7.3.
Any organic molecular entity that contains at least one C=C bond.
A ketone hydrate that is naphthalene-1,2,3,4-tetrone in which water has been added to the keto groups at positions 2 and 3. It has been used as an antiviral agent in nasal ointment.
An inorganic sodium salt having nitrite as the counterion. Used as a food preservative and antidote to cyanide poisoning.
A fatty acid anion containing 19 carbons and 0 double bonds. Major species at pH 7.3.
A saturated fatty acid anion containing 21 carbons (R(1) = C20H41). It is the major species at pH 7.3.

A hydroxy fatty acid that is a straight-chain fatty acid in which one of the hydrogens attached to the carbon adjacent to the terminal methyl group (i.e. at the (omega-1) position) is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of hexadecanoic acid (palmitic acid); major species at pH 7.3.
A very long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of tricosanoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An (omega-1)-hydroxy fatty acid that is henicosanoic acid in which the 20-pro-R hydrogen is replaced by a hydroxy group.
An (omega-1)-hydroxy fatty acid that is valeric acid in which the 4-pro-R hydrogen is replaced by a hydroxy group.
A monocarboxylic acid in which the carbon of the carboxy group is directly attached to a C=C or C#C bond.
